:"1145","about 1103":"omkring 1103","about 1125":"omkring 1125","1165":"1165","about 1145":"omkring 1145","1082":"1082","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Berwick, Sussex, England":"Berwick, Sussex, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"nl":{"about 1103–about 1145":"circa 1103–circa 1145","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1125–1201":"1125–1201","1103–1145":"1103–1145","1106":"1106","1103":"1103","1125":"1125","1124":"1124","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","about 1103":"circa 1103","about 1125":"circa 1125","1165":"1165","about 1145":"circa 1145","1082":"1082","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Berwick, Sussex, England":"Berwick, Sussex, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"en":{"about 1103–about 1145":"about 1103–about 1145","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1125–1201":"1125–1201","1103–1145":"1103–1145","1106":"1106","1103":"1103","1125":"1125","1124":"1124","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","about 1103":"about 1103","about 1125":"about 1125","1165":"1165","about 1145":"about 1145","1082":"1082","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Berwick, Sussex, England":"Berwick, Sussex, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":3,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Jane was born about 1103, in Berwick, Dorset, England. She married Sir Robert de Russell I in 1124, in Berwick, Sussex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1145, in Beaminster, Dorset, England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"about 1103–about 1145":"umbes 1103–umbes 1145","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1125–1201":"1125–1201","1103–1145":"1103–1145","1106":"1106","1103":"1103","1125":"1125","1124":"1124","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","about 1103":"umbes 1103","about 1125":"umbes 1125","1165":"1165","about 1145":"umbes 1145","1082":"1082","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Berwick, Sussex, England":"Berwick, Sussex, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"fi":{"about 1103–about 1145":"noin 1103–noin 1145","1082–1165":"1082–1165","1125–1201":"1125–1201","1103–1145":"1103–1145","1106":"1106","1103":"1103","1125":"1125","1124":"1124","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","about 1103":"noin 1103","about 1125":"noin 1125","1165":"1165","about 1145":"noin 1145","1082":"1082","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Berwick, Sussex, England":"Berwick, Sussex, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England